- - - ( JSON ) - - -

- JSON or Java Script Opbject Notation, commonly used for API's and Configs 


** ( JSON Types ):

• Strings 
• Numbers
• Booleans 
• NULL
• Arrays
• Objects


** ( Example Syntax ):

[ // Array
  { //Object 1
    str: "Hello, world",         // String
    num: 42,                     // Number
    bool: true,                  // Boolean
    empty: null,                 // NULL
    arr: [1, 2, 3],              // Array
    obj: { name: "Alice" }       // Object
  },
  { //Object 2
    str: "Goodbye!",            
    num: 3.14,                  
    bool: false,                 
    empty: null,                 
    arr: ["apple", "banana"],   
    obj: { age: 25 }             
  }
]



** ( JSON.stringify() & JSON.parse() ):

- JSON.stringify( "object" / "array" ) = converts, JS object / array -> A Single String 

- JSON.parse( "object" / "array" ) = converts, JS string -> JSON object / array ( depends on the syntax )



** ( fetch(url, options) & .json() ):



- ( fetch(url, options) ):

• a promise based function used for making HTTP messages to fetch resources
  ( JSON, images, files )

• fetch(), returns the whole HTTP response as an "JS object" ( but not the actual data in the "body" yet )

• since it's promise based, you can use ( async/await, .then(), .catch() )


( Syntax ):

- "url", the resource your trying to make a request 
- "options", object that defines how the request behaves, it includes...
• HTTP method (GET, POST, etc.)
• Headers
• Body (for POST/PUT)
• Mode (e.g., CORS)
• Credentials (cookies/auth)


( Example of fetch w/POST method ):

fetch(
 "url", 
 {
 method : "POST",
 headers : { 'Content-Type' : 'application/json' },
 body: JSON.stringify({ name: 'user 1' })
 }
).then( response => { return response.json() })
.then( (data) => { console.log(data); })
.catch( (error) => { console.log('ERROR'); }); 

/* 
Example Explanation:
• A request has been made on a specific URL using a "POST" method 
• The request body, is converted into string 
• if request successful, fetch will return a promise, & ".then" will parse the returned value
• After parsing, the contents of the data section ( obj ) is outputted 
• if request failed, Outputs : Error 
*/ 



- ( .json() ):

• a method that reads the "body" of that response and parses it into a usable "JS object"

• returns a Promise, which, when resolved, gives you that "JS object"


( Example: )

fetch( "URL" )) //Returns a HTTP response as an object
.then( (response) => { response.json() } ) //Returns a Promise which, when resolved, gives you a HTTP response body as an object